column10:
One hundred meters wide, but only a few inches deep;
The honeymoon phase lasts a week or two before you discover the hollow centre within

That is why most reviews you will see end around the 50 hour mark, and do not increase post-review

In my experience, Palworld is best enjoyed when NOT played with the 'slave driver' role in mind. Drawing on that pokemon lookalike parallel;

Palworld has actually forced me to care DEEPLY about how my Pals are doing in a way that Pokemon could never hope to do. If your heavy hitters in Pokemon go down, you go to a pokemon center, heal up, and move on. If your heavy hitters go down in Palworld? It brings your progress to a halt, because now you need to wait for ten minutes for them to recover, and you have no one to blame but yourself, getting into a situation over your head.

If the Pals that you assign to your base get injured, they work slower, and if this goes on long enough, they go down as well. If they run out of food and are starving, they'll crowd you, looking for food, and it genuinely feels bad if I can't feed them. For that engagement alone, I love this game, and CAN NOT wait to see where Pocketpair goes from here.
